ux  ."]},{"name":"Molineaux","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Staffordshire): variant of   Molyneux  ."]},{"name":"Molyneaux","meanings":["English and Irish (of Norman origin): variant of   Molyneux  . Compare   Mallonee  ."]}]},{"name":"Ellen","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Helen  , although now no longer associated with that name. Initial <i>H-</i> tended to be added and dropped rather capriciously, leading to many doublets (  compare for example  Esther   and   Hester  ). It is also sometimes used as a short form of   Eleanor  , to which, however, it is unrelated."],"variants":[{"name":"Eleanor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Ellen Molyneux was born in 1418, in Lancashire, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Lady Helen  of Hornby Harrington*. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Roger Ashton."},"et":{"1418–":"1418–Surnud","1412–1454":"1412–1454","1416–1417":"1416–1417","1418–Female":"1418–Surnud","1423–1486":"1423–1486","1445–1512":"1445–1512","1483–Male":"1483–Surnud","1398–Female":"1398–Surnud","<1483>":"1483","1483":"1483","1512":"1512","1445":"1445","1423":"1423","1412":"1412","1454":"1454","1398":"1398","1486":"1486","about 1445":"umbes 1445","1418":"1418","1417":"1417","1416":"1416","Of Makefield, Ashton, Lancashire, England":"Ashton in Makerfield, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":